<DOC><DOCNO> AP890524-0112 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-89 1229EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Bangladesh-Drought     05-24 0181</FIRST><SECOND>AM-BRF--Bangladesh-Drought,0187</SECOND><HEAD>Drought Kills $93 Million in Crops</HEAD><DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The last three months of a droughtkilled about $93 million in spring crops, the government saidWednesday.   Agriculture Minister Abdul Munem told Parliament that 16 of 64districts were hit by the drought that also claimed 150 lives.   Munem said experts had estimated a spring harvest of 5.6 milliontons of rice and wheat, about one-fourth of the country's annualneeds of 18.5 million tons.   The country produces 17 million tons of grain every year for its110 million people and imports the rest. Bangladesh, one of theworld's poorest nations, has an annual per capita income of $160.   Munem did not say how much crop was lost but experts hadpredicted that more than half of the grain might be destroyed bydrought.   Bangladesh alternates between dry and wet spells and last yearmore than 1,400 people were killed in floods that inundatedthree-fourths of the nation, the size of Wisconsin.   Another 1,100 died in a cyclone in November. A tornado lastmonth killed 1,100 people.</TEXT></DOC>